Name: Aborted_clients
Meaning: The number of connections that were aborted because the client died without closing the connection properly.

Name: Aborted_connects
Meaning: The number of failed attempts to connect to the MySQL server.

Name: Aborted_connects_preauth
Meaning: Number of connection attempts that were aborted prior to authentication (regardless of whether or not an error occured).

Name: Access_denied_errors
Meaning: Number of access denied errors.

Name: Acl_column_grants
Meaning: Number of column permissions granted (rows in the mysql.columns_priv table).

Name: Acl_database_grants
Meaning: Number of database permissions granted (rows in the mysql.db table).

Name: Acl_function_grants
Meaning: Number of function permissions granted (rows in the mysql.procs_priv table with a routine type of FUNCTION).

Name: Acl_procedure_grants
Meaning: Number of procedure permissions granted (rows in the mysql.procs_priv table with a routine type of PROCEDURE).

Name: Acl_role_grants
Meaning: Number of role permissions granted (rows in the mysql.roles_mapping table).

Name: Acl_table_grants
Meaning: Number of table permissions granted (rows in the mysql.tables_priv table).

Name: Binlog_cache_disk_use
Meaning: The number of transactions that used the temporary binary log cache but that exceeded the value of binlog_cache_size and used a temporary file to store statements from the transaction.

Name: Binlog_cache_use
Meaning: The number of transactions that used the binary log cache.

Name: Binlog_stmt_cache_disk_use
Meaning: The number of nontransactional statements that used the binary log statement cache but that exceeded the value of binlog_stmt_cache_size and used a temporary file to store those statements.

Name: Binlog_stmt_cache_use
Meaning: The number of nontransactional statements that used the binary log statement cache.

Name: Busy_time
Meaning: Cumulative time in seconds of activity on connections.

Name: Bytes_received
Meaning: The number of bytes received from all clients.

Name: Bytes_sent
Meaning: The number of bytes sent to all clients.

Name: Com_admin_commands
Meaning: Number of admin commands executed. These include table dumps, change users, binary log dumps, shutdowns, pings and debugs.

Name: Com_alter_db
Meaning: Number of ALTER DATABASE commands

Name: Com_alter_db_upgrade
Meaning: Number of ALTER DATABASE ... UPGRADE commands executed.

Name: Com_alter_event
Meaning: Number of ALTER EVENT commands executed

Name: Com_alter_function
Meaning: Number of ALTER FUNCTION commands executed

Name: Com_change_db
Meaning: Number of USE database_name commands executed.

Name: Com_commit
Meaning: Number of COMMIT commands executed. Differs from Handler_commit, which counts internal commit statements.

Name: Com_compound_sql
Meaning: Number of compund sql statements

Name: Com_create_sequence
Meaning: Number of CREATE SEQUENCE commands executed

Name: Com_dealloc_sql
Meaning: Number of DROP PREPARE or DEALLOCATE commands executed.

Name: Com_delete
Meaning: Number of DELETE commands executed. Differs from Handler_delete, which counts the number of times rows have been deleted from tables.

Name: Com_delete_multi
Meaning: Number of multi-table DELETE commands executed

Name: Com_empty_query
Meaning: Number of queries to the server that do not produce SQL queries.

Name: Com_explain_other
Meaning: Indicates the number of EXPLAIN FOR CONNECTION statements executed.

Name: Com_ha_close
Meaning: Number of HANDLER table_name CLOSE commands executed

Name: Com_ha_open
Meaning: Number of HANDLER table_name OPEN commands executed.

Name: Com_ha_read
Meaning: Number of HANDLER table_name READ commands executed

Name: Com_insert_select
Meaning: Number of INSERT commands executed.

Name: Com_install_component
Meaning: Number of INSERT SELECT commands executed.

Name: Com_stmt_close
Meaning: Prepared statement deallocation

Name: Com_stmt_execute
Meaning: Prepared statement execution

Name: Com_stmt_prepare
Meaning: Prepared statement creation

Name: Com_stmt_reprepare
Meaning: Number of times statements were automatically reprepared by the server, for example, after metadata changes to tables or views referred to by the statement. A reprepare operation increments Com_stmt_reprepare, and also Com_stmt_prepare.

Name: Connection_errors_accept
Meaning: The number of errors that occurred during calls to accept() on the listening port.

Name: Connection_errors_internal
Meaning: The number of connections refused due to internal errors in the server, such as failure to start a new thread or an out-of-memory condition.

Name: Connection_errors_max_connections
Meaning: The number of connections refused because the server max_connections limit was reached.

Name: Connection_errors_peer_address
Meaning: The number of errors that occurred while searching for connecting client IP addresses.

Name: Connection_errors_select
Meaning: The number of errors that occurred during calls to OS select() or poll() on the listening port. (Failure of this operation does not necessarily means a client connection was rejected.)

Name: Connection_errors_tcpwrap
Meaning: The number of connections refused by the libwrap library.

Name: Connections
Meaning: The number of connection attempts (successful or not) to the MySQL server.

Name: Created_tmp_disk_tables
Meaning: The number of internal on-disk temporary tables created by the server while executing statements.

Name: Created_tmp_files
Meaning: How many temporary files mysqld has created.

Name: Created_tmp_tables
Meaning: The number of internal temporary tables created by the server while executing statements.

Name: Delayed_errors
Meaning: Deprecated.  This status variable is deprecated (because DELAYED inserts are not supported)

Name: Delayed_insert_threads
Meaning: Deprecated.  This status variable is deprecated (because DELAYED inserts are not supported)

Name: Delayed_writes
Meaning: Deprecated.  This status variable is deprecated (because DELAYED inserts are not supported)

Name: Delete_scan
Meaning: Number of DELETEs that required a full table scan

Name: Empty_queries
Meaning: Number of queries returning no results. Note this is not the same as Com_empty_query

Name: Error_log_expired_events
Meaning: The number of events discarded from the Performance Schema error_log table to make room for new events.

Name: Executed_events
Meaning: Number of times events created with CREATE EVENT have executed.

Name: Executed_triggers
Meaning: Number of times triggers created with CREATE TRIGGER have executed

Name: Feature_application_time_periods
Meaning: Number of times a table created with periods has been opened

Name: Feature_check_constraint
Meaning: Number of times constraints were checked. The global value can be flushed by FLUSH STATUS

Name: Feature_custom_aggregate_functions
Meaning: Number of queries which make use of custom aggregate functions

Name: Feature_dynamic_columns
Meaning: Number of times the COLUMN_CREATE() function was used

Name: Feature_fulltext
Meaning: Number of times the MATCH … AGAINST() function was used

Name: Feature_gis
Meaning: Number of times a table with a any of the geometry columns was opened

Name: Feature_invisible_columns
Meaning: Number of invisible columns in all opened tables.

Name: Feature_json
Meaning: Number of times JSON functionality has been used, such as one of the JSON functions. Does not include the CONNECT engine JSON type, or EXPLAIN/ANALYZE FORMAT=JSON

Name: Feature_locale
Meaning: Number of times the @@lc_messages variable was assigned into.

Name: Feature_subquery
Meaning: Number of subqueries (excluding subqueries in the FROM clause) used

Name: Feature_system_versioning
Meaning: Number of times a table WITH SYSTEM VERSIONING has been opened.

Name: Feature_timezone
Meaning: Number of times an explicit timezone (excluding UTC and SYSTEM) was specified

Name: Feature_trigger
Meaning: Number of triggers loaded

Name: Feature_window_functions
Meaning: Number of times window functions were used.

Name: Feature_xml
Meaning: Number of times XML functions (EXTRACTVALUE() and UPDATEXML()) were used

Name: Flush_commands
Meaning: The number of times the server flushes tables, whether because a user executed a FLUSH TABLES statement or due to internal server operation. It is also incremented by receipt of a COM_REFRESH packet. This is in contrast to Com_flush, which indicates how many FLUSH statements have been executed, whether FLUSH TABLES, FLUSH LOGS, and so forth.

Name: Handler_commit
Meaning: The number of internal COMMIT statements.

Name: Handler_delete
Meaning: The number of times that rows have been deleted from tables.

Name: Handler_discover
Meaning: Discovery is when the server asks the NDBCLUSTER storage engine if it knows about a table with a given name. Handler_discover indicates the number of times that tables have been discovered in this way

Name: Handler_external_lock
Meaning: The server increments this variable for each call to its external_lock() function, which generally occurs at the beginning and end of access to a table instance. There might be differences among storage engines. This variable can be used, for example, to discover for a statement that accesses a partitioned table how many partitions were pruned before locking occurred: Check how much the counter increased for the statement, subtract 2 (2 calls for the table itself), then divide by 2 to get the number of partitions locked.

Name: Handler_icp_attempts
Meaning: Number of times pushed index condition was checked. ("Using index condition" in EXPLAIN). The smaller the ratio of Handler_icp_attempts to Handler_icp_match the better the filtering. See Index Condition Pushdown

Name: Handler_icp_match
Meaning: Number of times pushed index condition was matched. The smaller the ratio of Handler_icp_attempts to Handler_icp_match the better the filtering

Name: Handler_mrr_init
Meaning: Counts how many multi-range read (MRR) scans were performed ("Rowid-ordered scan" in EXPLAIN).

Name: Handler_mrr_key_refills
Meaning: Number of times MRR key buffer was refilled (not counting the initial fill). A non-zero value indicates there wasn't enough memory to do key sort-and-sweep passes in one go

Name: Handler_mrr_rowid_refills
Meaning: Number of times MRR rowid buffer was refilled (not counting the initial fill). A non-zero value indicates there wasn't enough memory to do rowid sort-and-sweep passes in one go

Name: Handler_prepare
Meaning: Number of two-phase commit prepares

Name: Handler_read_first
Meaning: Number of requests to read the first row from an index. A high value indicates many full index scans

Name: Handler_read_key
Meaning: Number of row read requests based on an index value. A high value indicates indexes are regularly being used, which is usually positive

Name: Handler_read_last
Meaning: Number of requests to read the last key in an index. With ORDER BY, the server issues a first-key request followed by several next-key requests, whereas with ORDER BY DESC, the server issues a last-key request followed by several previous-key requests.

Name: Handler_read_next
Meaning: The number of requests to read the next row in key order. This value is incremented if you are querying an index column with a range constraint or if you are doing an index scan.

Name: Handler_read_prev
Meaning: The number of requests to read the previous row in key order. This read method is mainly used to optimize ORDER BY ... DESC.

Name: Handler_read_retry
Meaning: Number of read retrys triggered by semi_consistent_read (InnoDB feature)

Name: Handler_read_rnd
Meaning: The number of requests to read a row based on a fixed position. This value is high if you are doing a lot of queries that require sorting of the result. You probably have a lot of queries that require MySQL to scan entire tables or you have joins that do not use keys properly.

Name: Handler_read_rnd_deleted
Meaning: Number of requests to delete a row based on its position

Name: Handler_read_rnd_next
Meaning: The number of requests to read the next row in the data file. This value is high if you are doing a lot of table scans. Generally this suggests that your tables are not properly indexed or that your queries are not written to take advantage of the indexes you have.

Name: Handler_rollback
Meaning: The number of requests for a storage engine to perform a rollback operation

Name: Handler_savepoint
Meaning: The number of requests for a storage engine to place a savepoint

Name: Handler_savepoint_rollback
Meaning: The number of requests for a storage engine to roll back to a savepoint

Name: Handler_tmp_delete
Meaning: Number of requests to delete a row in a temporary table

Name: Handler_tmp_update
Meaning: Number of requests to update a row to a temporary table

Name: Handler_tmp_write
Meaning: Number of requests to write a row to a temporary table

Name: Handler_update
Meaning: Number of requests to update a row in a non-temporary table

Name: Handler_write
Meaning: Number of requests to insert a row in a non-temporary table

Name: Innodb_adaptive_hash_hash_searches
Meaning: Hash searches

Name: Innodb_adaptive_hash_non_hash_searches
Meaning: Non-hash searches

Name: Innodb_background_log_sync
Meaning: number of times the InnoDB source thread has written and flushed the redo log

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_LRU_flushed
Meaning: Number of buffer pool pages which have been flushed from the LRU list, i.e., too old pages which had to be flushed in order to make buffer pool room to read in new data pages

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_lru_flushed
Meaning: Number of buffer pool pages which have been flushed from the LRU list, i.e., too old pages which had to be flushed in order to make buffer pool room to read in new data pages

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_flushed
Meaning: The number of requests to flush pages from the InnoDB buffer pool

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_lru_freed
Meaning: Monitor the number of pages that were freed by a buffer pool LRU eviction scan, without flushing

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_made_not_young
Meaning: The total number of pages not made young in the buffer pool LRU list (pages that have remained in the “old” sublist without being made young).

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_made_young
Meaning: The total number of pages made young in the buffer pool LRU list (moved to the head of sublist of “new” pages).

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_read_ahead
Meaning: The number of pages read into the InnoDB buffer pool by the read-ahead background thread.

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_read_ahead_evicted
Meaning: The number of pages read into the InnoDB buffer pool by the read-ahead background thread that were subsequently evicted without having been accessed by queries

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_read_ahead_rnd
Meaning: The number of “random” read-aheads initiated by InnoDB. This happens when a query scans a large portion of a table but in random order

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_read_requests
Meaning: The number of logical read requests.

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_reads
Meaning: The number of logical reads that InnoDB could not satisfy from the buffer pool, and had to read directly from disk

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_wait_free
Meaning: Normally, writes to the InnoDB buffer pool happen in the background. When InnoDB needs to read or create a page and no clean pages are available, InnoDB flushes some dirty pages first and waits for that operation to finish. This counter counts instances of these waits. If innodb_buffer_pool_size has been set properly, this value should be small

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_write_requests
Meaning: The number of writes done to the InnoDB buffer pool

Name: Innodb_buffered_aio_submitted
Meaning: The number of submitted buffered asynchronous I/O requests.

Name: Innodb_data_fsyncs
Meaning: The number of fsync() operations so far. The frequency of fsync() calls is influenced by the setting of the innodb_flush_method configuration option. Counts the number of fdatasync() operations if innodb_use_fdatasync is enabled.

Name: Innodb_data_read
Meaning: The amount of data read since the server was started (in bytes)

Name: Innodb_data_reads
Meaning: The total number of data reads (OS file reads)

Name: Innodb_data_writes
Meaning: The total number of data writes

Name: Innodb_data_written
Meaning: The amount of data written so far, in bytes.

Name: Innodb_dblwr_pages_written
Meaning: The number of pages that have been written to the doublewrite buffer.

Name: Innodb_dblwr_writes
Meaning: The number of doublewrite operations that have been performed

Name: Innodb_log_waits
Meaning: The number of times that the log buffer was too small and a wait was required for it to be flushed before continuing

Name: Innodb_log_write_requests
Meaning: The number of write requests for the InnoDB redo log.

Name: Innodb_log_writes
Meaning: The number of physical writes to the InnoDB redo log file.

Name: Innodb_os_log_fsyncs
Meaning: The number of fsync() writes done to the InnoDB redo log files

Name: Innodb_os_log_written
Meaning: The number of bytes written to the InnoDB redo log files.

Name: Innodb_pages_created
Meaning: The number of pages created by operations on InnoDB tables

Name: Innodb_pages_read
Meaning: The number of pages read from the InnoDB buffer pool by operations on InnoDB tables.

Name: Innodb_pages_written
Meaning: The number of pages written by operations on InnoDB tables

Name: Innodb_row_lock_time
Meaning: The total time spent in acquiring row locks for InnoDB tables, in milliseconds

Name: Innodb_row_lock_waits
Meaning: The number of times operations on InnoDB tables had to wait for a row lock

Name: Innodb_rows_deleted
Meaning: The number of rows deleted from InnoDB tables

Name: Innodb_rows_inserted
Meaning: The number of rows inserted into InnoDB tables

Name: Innodb_rows_read
Meaning: The number of rows red from InnoDB tables

Name: Innodb_rows_updated
Meaning: The number of rows updated in InnoDB tables

Name: Innodb_system_rows_deleted
Meaning: The number of rows deleted from InnoDB tables belonging to system-created schemas

Name: Innodb_system_rows_inserted
Meaning: The number of rows inserted into InnoDB tables belonging to system-created schemas.

Name: Innodb_system_rows_read
Meaning: The number of rows read from InnoDB tables belonging to system-created schemas

Name: Innodb_system_rows_updated
Meaning: The number of rows updated InnoDB tables belonging to system-created schemas

Name: Innodb_truncated_status_writes
Meaning: The number of times output from the SHOW ENGINE INNODB STATUS statement has been truncated

Name: Innodb_undo_tablespaces_active
Meaning: The number of active undo tablespaces. Includes both implicit (InnoDB-created) and explicit (user-created) undo tablespaces. For information about undo tablespaces

Name: Innodb_undo_tablespaces_explicit
Meaning: The number of user-created undo tablespaces

Name: Innodb_undo_tablespaces_implicit
Meaning: The number of undo tablespaces created by InnoDB. Two default undo tablespaces are created by InnoDB when the MySQL instance is initialized

Name: Innodb_undo_tablespaces_total
Meaning: The total number of undo tablespaces. Includes both implicit (InnoDB-created) and explicit (user-created) undo tablespaces, active and inactive

Name: Key_read_requests
Meaning: The number of requests to read a key block from the MyISAM key cache

Name: Key_reads
Meaning: The number of physical reads of a key block from disk into the MyISAM key cache. If Key_reads is large, then your key_buffer_size value is probably too small. The cache miss rate can be calculated as Key_reads/Key_read_requests

Name: Key_write_requests
Meaning: The number of requests to write a key block to the MyISAM key cache

Name: Key_writes
Meaning: The number of physical writes of a key block from the MyISAM key cache to disk

Name: Master_gtid_wait_count
Meaning: The number of attempts to connect to locked user accounts.

Name: Max_execution_time_exceeded
Meaning: The number of SELECT statements for which the execution timeout was exceeded

Name: Max_execution_time_set
Meaning: The number of SELECT statements for which a nonzero execution timeout was set. This includes statements that include a nonzero MAX_EXECUTION_TIME optimizer hint, and statements that include no such hint but execute while the timeout indicated by the max_execution_time system variable is nonzero

Name: Max_execution_time_set_failed
Meaning: The number of SELECT statements for which the attempt to set an execution timeout failed

Name: Opened_files
Meaning: The number of files that have been opened with my_open() (a mysys library function). Parts of the server that open files without using this function do not increment the count

Name: Opened_table_definitions
Meaning: The number of table definitions that have been cached

Name: Opened_tables
Meaning: The number of tables that have been opened. If Opened_tables is big, your table_open_cache value is probably too small

Name: Qcache_hits
Meaning: Number of requests served by the query cache. The global value can be flushed by FLUSH STATUS

Name: Qcache_inserts
Meaning: Number of queries ever cached in the query cache. The global value can be flushed by FLUSH

Name: Qcache_lowmem_prunes
Meaning: Number of pruning operations performed to remove old results to make space for new results in the query cache. The global value can be flushed by FLUSH STATU

Name: Qcache_not_cached
Meaning: Number of queries that are uncacheable by the query cache, or use SQL_NO_CACHE. The global value can be flushed by FLUSH STATUS

Name: Queries
Meaning: The number of statements executed by the server. This variable includes statements executed within stored programs, unlike the Questions variable. It does not count COM_PING or COM_STATISTICS commands.

Name: Questions
Meaning: The number of statements executed by the server. This includes only statements sent to the server by clients and not statements executed within stored programs, unlike the Queries variable. This variable does not count COM_PING, COM_STATISTICS, COM_STMT_PREPARE, COM_STMT_CLOSE, or COM_STMT_RESET commands

Name: Rows_read
Meaning: Number of requests to read a row (excluding temporary tables)

Name: Rows_tmp_read
Meaning: Number of requests to read a row in a temporary table

Name: Rpl_semi_sync_master_net_wait_time
Meaning: The total time in microseconds the source waited for replica replies. This variable is always 0, and is deprecated; expect it to be removed in a future version

Name: Rpl_semi_sync_master_net_waits
Meaning: The total number of times the source waited for replica replies

Name: Rpl_semi_sync_master_no_times
Meaning: The number of times the source turned off semisynchronous replication

Name: Rpl_semi_sync_master_no_tx
Meaning: The number of commits that were not acknowledged successfully by a replica

Name: Rpl_semi_sync_master_timefunc_failures
Meaning: The number of times the source failed when calling time functions such as gettimeofday()

Name: Rpl_semi_sync_master_tx_wait_time
Meaning: The total time in microseconds the source waited for transactions

Name: Rpl_semi_sync_master_tx_waits
Meaning: The total number of times the source waited for transactions

Name: Rpl_semi_sync_master_wait_pos_backtraverse
Meaning: The total number of times the source waited for an event with binary coordinates lower than events waited for previously. This can occur when the order in which transactions start waiting for a reply is different from the order in which their binary log events are written

Name: Rpl_semi_sync_master_yes_tx
Meaning: The number of commits that were acknowledged successfully by a replica

Name: Select_full_join
Meaning: The number of joins that perform table scans because they do not use indexes. If this value is not 0, you should carefully check the indexes of your tables

Name: Select_full_range_join
Meaning: The number of joins that used a range search on a reference table

Name: Select_range
Meaning: The number of joins that used ranges on the first table. This is normally not a critical issue even if the value is quite large

Name: Select_range_check
Meaning: The number of joins without keys that check for key usage after each row. If this is not 0, you should carefully check the indexes of your tables

Name: Select_scan
Meaning: The number of joins that did a full scan of the first table

Name: Slow_launch_threads
Meaning: The number of threads that have taken more than slow_launch_time seconds to create

Name: Slow_queries
Meaning: The number of queries that have taken more than long_query_time seconds. This counter increments regardless of whether the slow query log is enabled

Name: Sort_merge_passes
Meaning: The number of merge passes that the sort algorithm has had to do. If this value is large, you should consider increasing the value of the sort_buffer_size system variable.

Name: Sort_priority_queue_sorts
Meaning: The number of times that sorting was done through a priority queue.

Name: Sort_range
Meaning: The number of sorts that were done using ranges

Name: Sort_rows
Meaning: The number of sorted rows

Name: Sort_scan
Meaning: The number of sorts that were done by scanning the table

Name: Ssl_accept_renegotiates
Meaning: The number of negotiates needed to establish the connection

Name: Ssl_accepts
Meaning: The number of accepted SSL connections

Name: Ssl_callback_cache_hits
Meaning: The number of callback cache hits.

Name: Ssl_client_connects
Meaning: The number of SSL connection attempts to an SSL-enabled replication source server.

Name: Ssl_connect_renegotiates
Meaning: The number of negotiates needed to establish the connection to an SSL-enabled replication source server

Name: Ssl_finished_accepts
Meaning: The number of successful replica connections to an SSL-enabled replication source server.

Name: Ssl_session_cache_hits
Meaning: The number of SSL session cache hits

Name: Ssl_session_cache_misses
Meaning: The number of SSL session cache misses

Name: Ssl_session_cache_overflows
Meaning: The number of SSL session cache overflows

Name: Ssl_session_cache_timeouts
Meaning: The number of SSL session cache timeouts

Name: Ssl_sessions_reused
Meaning: How many SSL connections were reused from the cache.

Name: Ssl_used_session_cache_entries
Meaning: How many SSL session cache entries were used

Name: Syncs
Meaning: Number of times my_sync() has been called, or the number of times the server has had to force data to disk. Covers the binary log, .frm creation (if these operations are configured to sync) and some storage engines (Archive, CSV, Aria), but not XtraDB/InnoDB)

Name: Table_locks_immediate
Meaning: The number of times that a request for a table lock could be granted immediately

Name: Table_locks_waited
Meaning: The number of times that a request for a table lock could not be granted immediately and a wait was needed. If this is high and you have performance problems, you should first optimize your queries, and then either split your table or tables or use replication

Name: Table_open_cache_hits
Meaning: The number of hits for open tables cache lookups

Name: Table_open_cache_misses
Meaning: The number of misses for open tables cache lookups

Name: Table_open_cache_overflows
Meaning: The number of overflows for the open tables cache. This is the number of times, after a table is opened or closed, a cache instance has an unused entry and the size of the instance is larger than table_open_cache / table_open_cache_instances

Name: Tc_log_page_waits
Meaning: Number of times a two-phase commit was forced to wait for a free memory-mapped file-based transaction coordinator log page. The global value can be flushed by FLUSH STATUS

Name: Threads_created
Meaning: The number of threads created to handle connections. If Threads_created is big, you may want to increase the thread_cache_size value. The cache miss rate can be calculated as Threads_created/Connections

Name: Update_scan
Meaning: Number of updates that required a full table scan

Name: Uptime
Meaning: The number of seconds that the server has been up

Name: Uptime_since_flush_status
Meaning: The number of seconds since the most recent FLUSH STATUS statement

Name: Innodb_available_undo_logs
Meaning: Total number available InnoDB undo logs. Differs from the innodb_undo_logs system variable, which specifies the number of active undo logs

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_bytes_data
Meaning: The total number of bytes in the InnoDB buffer pool containing data. The number includes both dirty and clean pages. For more accurate memory usage calculations than with Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_data, when compressed tables cause the buffer pool to hold pages of different sizes

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_bytes_dirty
Meaning: The total current number of bytes held in dirty pages in the InnoDB buffer pool. For more accurate memory usage calculations than with Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_dirty, when compressed tables cause the buffer pool to hold pages of different sizes

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_dump_status
Meaning: A text description of the progress or final status of the last Innodb buffer pool dump

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_load_incomplete
Meaning: Whether or not the loaded buffer pool is incomplete, for example after a shutdown or abort during innodb buffer pool load from file caused an incomplete save

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_load_status
Meaning: The status of a buffer pool load operation

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_data
Meaning: The number of pages in the InnoDB buffer pool containing data. The number includes both dirty and clean pages. When using compressed tables, the reported Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_data value may be larger than Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_total

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_dirty
Meaning: The current number of dirty pages in the InnoDB buffer pool

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_free
Meaning: The number of free pages in the InnoDB buffer pool

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_misc
Meaning: The number of pages in the InnoDB buffer pool that are busy because they have been allocated for administrative overhead, such as row locks or the adaptive hash index.

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_old
Meaning: The number of buffer pool pages which are considered to be old

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_total
Meaning: The total size of the InnoDB buffer pool, in pages. When using compressed tables, the reported Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_data value may be larger than Innodb_buffer_pool_pages_total

Name: Innodb_buffer_pool_resize_status
Meaning: The status of an operation to resize the InnoDB buffer pool dynamically, triggered by setting the innodb_buffer_pool_size parameter dynamically. The innodb_buffer_pool_size parameter is dynamic, which allows you to resize the buffer pool without restarting the server.

Name: Innodb_checkpoint_age
Meaning: The checkpoint age ,equivalent to subtracting "Last checkpoint at" from "Log sequence number".

Name: Innodb_checkpoint_max_age
Meaning: The largest checkpoint age.

Name: Innodb_data_pending_fsyncs
Meaning: Number of pending InnoDB fsync (sync-to-disk) calls. fsync call frequency can be influenced by the innodb_flush_method configuration option

Name: Innodb_data_pending_reads
Meaning: Number of pending InnoDB reads

Name: Innodb_data_pending_writes
Meaning: Number of pending InnoDB writes

Name: Innodb_have_atomic_builtins
Meaning: Whether the server has been built with atomic instructions, provided by the CPU ensuring that critical low-level operations can't be interrupted.

Name: Innodb_have_bzip2
Meaning: Whether the server has the bzip2 compression method available

Name: Innodb_have_lz4
Meaning: Whether the server has the lz4 compression method available

Name: Innodb_have_lzma
Meaning: Whether the server has the lzma compression method available

Name: Innodb_have_lzo
Meaning: Whether the server has the lzo compression method available

Name: Innodb_have_snappy
Meaning: Whether the server has the snappy compression method available

Name: Innodb_history_list_length
Meaning: History list length

Name: Innodb_ibuf_free_list
Meaning: Insert buffer free list length

Name: Innodb_ibuf_segment_size
Meaning: Insert buffer segment size

Name: Innodb_ibuf_size
Meaning: Insert buffer suze

Name: Innodb_lsn_current
Meaning: Current log sequence number

Name: Innodb_lsn_flushed
Meaning: Log sequence number most recently flushed to disk

Name: Innodb_lsn_last_checkpoint
Meaning: Log sequence number of last checkpoint

Name: Innodb_max_trx_id
Meaning: Maximum transaction id

Name: Innodb_mem_adaptive_hash
Meaning: Adaptive hash index size

Name: Innodb_mem_dictionary
Meaning: In-memory data dictionary size

Name: Innodb_mem_total
Meaning: Total memory InnoDB has allocated in the process heap.

Name: Innodb_oldest_view_low_limit_trx_id
Meaning: Transaction id

Name: Innodb_onlineddl_pct_progress
Meaning: Progress of in-place alter table. It might be not so accurate because in-place alter is highly dependent on disk and buffer pool status

Name: Innodb_onlineddl_rowlog_pct_used
Meaning: Row log buffer usage in 5-digit integer 10000=100%

Name: Innodb_onlineddl_rowlog_rows
Meaning: Number of rows stored in the row log buffer

Name: Innodb_page_compression_saved
Meaning: Memory saved by page compression

Name: Innodb_page_compression_trim_sect1024
Meaning: Number of TRIM operations performed for the page-compression/NVM Compression workload for the 1KiB block-size

Name: Innodb_page_compression_trim_sect16384
Meaning: Number of TRIM operations performed for the page-compression/NVM Compression workload for the 16KiB block-size

Name: Innodb_page_compression_trim_sect2048
Meaning: Number of TRIM operations performed for the page-compression/NVM Compression workload for the 2KiB block-size

Name: Innodb_page_compression_trim_sect32768
Meaning: Number of TRIM operations performed for the page-compression/NVM Compression workload for the 32KiB block-size

Name: Innodb_page_compression_trim_sect4096
Meaning: Number of TRIM operations performed for the page-compression/NVM Compression workload for the 4KiB block-size

Name: Innodb_page_compression_trim_sect512
Meaning: Number of TRIM operations performed for the page-compression/NVM Compression workload for the 512 byte block-size

Name: Innodb_page_compression_trim_sect8192
Meaning: Number of TRIM operations performed for the page-compression/NVM Compression workload for the 8KiB block-size

Name: Innodb_page_size
Meaning: Page size used by InnoDB. Defaults to 16KB, can be compiled with a different value

Name: Innodb_pages0_read
Meaning: Counter for keeping track of reads of the first page of InnoDB data files

Name: Innodb_purge_trx_id
Meaning: oldest transaction id whose records have not yet been purged

Name: Innodb_redo_log_enabled
Meaning: Whether redo logging is enabled or disabled. Introduced in MySQL 8.0.21

Name: Innodb_row_lock_current_waits
Meaning: The number of row locks currently being waited for by operations on InnoDB tables

Name: Innodb_row_lock_time_avg
Meaning: The average time to acquire a row lock for InnoDB tables, in milliseconds

Name: Innodb_row_lock_time_max
Meaning: The maximum time to acquire a row lock for InnoDB tables, in milliseconds

Name: Innodb_scan_data_size
Meaning: Size of data in all InnoDB pages read inside a query

Name: Innodb_scan_deleted_recs_size
Meaning: Size of deleted records in all InnoDB pages read inside a query

Name: Innodb_scan_pages_contiguous
Meaning: Number of contiguous page reads in a query

Name: Innodb_scan_pages_disjointed
Meaning: Number of disjointed page reads in a query

Name: Innodb_scan_pages_total_seek_distance
Meaning: Total seek distance when moving between pages

Name: Innodb_scrub_background_page_reorganizations
Meaning: Relates to tablespace encryption

Name: Innodb_scrub_background_page_split_failures_missing_index
Meaning: Relates to tablespace encryption

Name: Innodb_scrub_background_page_split_failures_out_of_filespace
Meaning: Relates to tablespace encryption

Name: Innodb_scrub_background_page_split_failures_underflow
Meaning: Relates to tablespace encryption

Name: Innodb_scrub_background_page_split_failures_unknown
Meaning: Relates to tablespace encryption

Name: Innodb_scrub_background_page_splits
Meaning: Relates to tablespace encryption

Name: Innodb_scrub_log
Meaning: Relates to tablespace encryption

Name: Key_blocks_not_flushed
Meaning: The number of key blocks in the MyISAM key cache that have changed but have not yet been flushed to disk

Name: Key_blocks_unused
Meaning: The number of unused blocks in the MyISAM key cache. You can use this value to determine how much of the key cache is in use

Name: Key_blocks_used
Meaning: The number of used blocks in the MyISAM key cache. This value is a high-water mark that indicates the maximum number of blocks that have ever been in use at one time

Name: Last_query_cost
Meaning: The total cost of the last compiled query as computed by the query optimizer. This is useful for comparing the cost of different query plans for the same query. The default value of 0 means that no query has been compiled yet. The default value is 0. Last_query_cost has session scope.

Name: Last_query_partial_plans
Meaning: The number of iterations the query optimizer made in execution plan construction for the previous query. Last_query_cost has session scope.

Name: Max_used_connections
Meaning: The maximum number of connections that have been in use simultaneously since the server started

Name: Max_used_connections_time
Meaning: The time at which Max_used_connections reached its current value

Name: Not_flushed_delayed_rows
Meaning: This status variable is deprecated (because DELAYED inserts are not supported); expect it to be removed in a future release

Name: Ongoing_anonymous_transaction_count
Meaning: Shows the number of ongoing transactions which have been marked as anonymous. This can be used to ensure that no further transactions are waiting to be processed

Name: Open_files
Meaning: The number of files that are open. This count includes regular files opened by the server. It does not include other types of files such as sockets or pipes. Also, the count does not include files that storage engines open using their own internal functions rather than asking the server level to do so

Name: Open_streams
Meaning: The number of streams that are open (used mainly for logging).

Name: Open_table_definitions
Meaning: The number of cached table definitions

Name: Open_tables
Meaning: The number of tables that are open.

Name: Prepared_stmt_count
Meaning: The current number of prepared statements.

Name: analyze_sample_percentage
Meaning: Percentage of rows from the table ANALYZE TABLE will sample to collect table statistics. Set to 0 to let MariaDB decide what percentage of rows to sample.

Name: aria_block_size
Meaning: Block size for Aria index pages.

Name: aria_checkpoint_interval
Meaning: Interval in seconds between automatic checkpoints.

Name: aria_checkpoint_log_activity
Meaning: Number of bytes that the transaction log has to grow between checkpoints before a new checkpoint is written to the log

Name: aria_force_start_after_recovery_failures
Meaning: Number of consecutive log recovery failures after which logs will be automatically deleted to cure the problem; 0 (the default) disables the feature

Name: aria_group_commit
Meaning: Specifies Aria group commit mode  none / hard / soft

Name: aria_group_commit_interval
Meaning: Interval between Aria group commits in microseconds

Name: aria_log_file_size
Meaning: Limit for Aria transaction log size

Name: auto_increment_increment
Meaning: Current increment to identity numbers

Name: auto_increment_offset
Meaning: Current starting point for identity numbers

Name: binlog_checksum
Meaning: Enabling this option causes the source to write checksums for events written to the binary log CRC32 / NONE

Name: binlog_row_event_max_size
Meaning: maximum size of a row-based binary log event

Name: delay_key_write
Meaning: ON/OFF/ALL Specifies how MyISAM tables handles CREATE TABLE DELAY_KEY_WRITE. If set to ON, the default, any DELAY KEY WRITEs are honored. The key buffer is then flushed only when the table closes, speeding up writes

Name: have_backup_locks
Meaning: Feature

Name: host_cache_size
Meaning: Available entries in host cache

Name: hostname
Meaning: Server machine's hostname

Name: identity
Meaning: LAST_INSERT_ID() value

Name: ignore_builtin_innodb
Meaning: Setting this to 1 results in the built-in InnoDB storage engine being ignored. In some versions of MariaDB, XtraDB is the default and is always present, so this variable is ignored and setting it results in a warning.

Name: innodb_adaptive_flushing
Meaning: If set to 1, the default, the server will dynamically adjust the flush rate of dirty pages in the InnoDB buffer pool. This assists to reduce brief bursts of I/O activity. If set to 0, adaptive flushing will only take place when the limit specified by innodb_adaptive_flushing_lwm is reached

Name: innodb_adaptive_flushing_lwm
Meaning: Adaptive flushing is enabled when this low water mark percentage of the InnoDB redo log capacity is reached. Takes effect even if innodb_adaptive_flushing is disabled

Name: innodb_adaptive_hash_index
Meaning: If set to 1, the default until MariaDB 10.5, the InnoDB hash index is enabled. Based on performance testing (MDEV-17492), the InnoDB adaptive hash index helps performance in mostly read-only workloads, and could slow down performance in other environments, especially DROP TABLE, TRUNCATE TABLE, ALTER TABLE, or DROP INDEX operations

Name: innodb_adaptive_hash_index_partitions
Meaning: Specifies the number of partitions for use in adaptive searching. If set to 1, no extra partitions are created. XtraDB-only. From MariaDB 10.2.6 (which uses InnoDB as default instead of XtraDB), this is an alias for innodb_adaptive_hash_index_parts to allow for easier upgrades

Name: innodb_adaptive_hash_index_parts
Meaning: Specifies the number of partitions for use in adaptive searching. If set to 1, no extra partitions are created.

Name: innodb_adaptive_max_sleep_delay
Meaning: Maximum time in microseconds to automatically adjust the innodb_thread_sleep_delay value to, based on the workload. Useful in extremely busy systems with hundreds of thousands of simultaneous connections. 0 disables any limit. Deprecated and ignored from MariaDB 10.5.5

Name: innodb_additional_mem_pool_size
Meaning: Size of the InnoDB memory pool used for storing information about internal data structures. Defaults to 8MB, if your application has many tables and a large structure, and this is exceeded, operating system memory will be allocated and warning messages written to the error log, in which case you should increase this value. Deprecated in MariaDB 10.0 and removed

Name: innodb_api_bk_commit_interval
Meaning: Time in seconds between auto-commits for idle connections using the InnoDB memcached interface

Name: innodb_api_disable_rowlock
Meaning: For use with MySQL's memcached

Name: innodb_api_enable_binlog
Meaning: For use with MySQL's memcached

Name: innodb_api_enable_mdl
Meaning: For use with MySQL's memcached

Name: innodb_api_trx_level
Meaning: For use with MySQL's memcached

Name: innodb_autoextend_increment
Meaning: Size to increment an auto-extending shared tablespace file when it becomes full. If innodb_file_per_table was set to 1, this setting does not apply to the resulting per-table tablespace files, which are automatically extended in their own way.

Name: innodb_autoinc_lock_mode
Meaning: The lock mode that is used when generating AUTO_INCREMENT values for InnoDB tables. 0:traditional 1:consecutive 2:interleaved. Galera Cluster requires 2.

Name: innodb_background_scrub_data_check_interval
Meaning: How often to check if spaces need scrubbing to overwrite deleted data

Name: innodb_background_scrub_data_compressed
Meaning: Enable scrubbing of compressed data by background threads

Name: innodb_background_scrub_data_interval
Meaning: Scrub spaces that were last scrubbed longer than this many seconds ago.

Name: innodb_background_scrub_data_uncompressed
Meaning: Enable scrubbing of uncompressed data by background threads

Name: innodb_buf_dump_status_frequency
Meaning: Determines how often the buffer pool dump status should be printed in the logs. For example, 10 means that the buffer pool dump status is printed when every 10% of the number of buffer pool pages are dumped. The default is 0 (only start and end status is printed)

Name: innodb_buffer_pool_chunk_size
Meaning: Chunk size used for dynamically resizing the buffer pool. Note that changing this setting can change the size of the buffer pool. When large-pages is used this value is effectively rounded up to the next multiple of large-page-size.

Name: innodb_buffer_pool_dump_at_shutdown
Meaning: Whether to record pages cached in the buffer pool on server shutdown, which reduces the length of the warmup the next time the server starts

Name: innodb_buffer_pool_dump_now
Meaning: Immediately records pages stored in the buffer pool.

Name: innodb_buffer_pool_dump_pct
Meaning: Dump only the hottest N% of each buffer pool,

Name: innodb_buffer_pool_filename
Meaning: The file that holds the buffer pool list of page numbers set by innodb_buffer_pool_dump_at_shutdown and innodb_buffer_pool_dump_now

Name: innodb_buffer_pool_instances
Meaning: If innodb_buffer_pool_size is set to more than 1GB, innodb_buffer_pool_instances divides the InnoDB buffer pool into this many instances.

Name: innodb_buffer_pool_load_abort
Meaning: Aborts the process of restoring buffer pool contents started by innodb_buffer_pool_load_at_startup or innodb_buffer_pool_load_now

Name: innodb_buffer_pool_load_at_startup
Meaning: Specifies whether the buffer pool is automatically warmed up when the server starts by loading the pages held earlier.

Name: innodb_buffer_pool_load_now
Meaning: Immediately warms up the buffer pool by loading the stored data pages

Name: innodb_buffer_pool_populate
Meaning: Preallocate pages in the buffer pool on starting up

Name: innodb_buffer_pool_size
Meaning: InnoDB buffer pool size. The primary value to adjust. On a dedicated server with entirely/primarily InnoDB tables, can be set up to 80% of total RAM.

Name: innodb_change_buffer_max_size
Meaning: Maximum size of the InnoDB Change Buffer (f/k/a Insert Buffer) as a percentage of the total buffer pool. The default is 25%, and this can be increased up to 50% for servers with high write activity, and lowered down to 0 for servers used exclusively for reporting

Name: innodb_change_buffering
Meaning: Sets how InnoDB change buffering is performed. Inserts / none / deletes / purges / changes / all

Name: innodb_checksum_algorithm
Meaning: Specifies how the InnoDB tablespace checksum is generated and verified. crc32  full_crc32 / strict_full_crc32 / none / strict_innodb / strict_none

Name: innodb_checksums
Meaning: Perform checksum validation on all pages read from disk, which provides extra fault tolerance.

Name: innodb_cleaner_lsn_age_factor
Meaning: XtraDB only.  Aggressive last sequence number (LSN) aging. high_checkpoint / legacy

Name: innodb_cmp_per_index_enabled
Meaning: Store per-index compression statistics in INFORMATION_SCHEMA.INNODB_CMP_PER_INDEX table. Expensive when ON.

Name: innodb_commit_concurrency
Meaning: Limit to the number of transaction threads that can can commit simultaneously. 0=no limit.

Name: innodb_compression_algorithm
Meaning: Algorithm for page compression.  none / zlib / lz4 / lzo / lzma / bzip2 / snappy

Name: innodb_compression_default
Meaning: Compression enabled by default for new tables

Name: innodb_compression_failure_threshold_pct
Meaning: Cutoff for expensive compression failures during updates.  0=none

Name: innodb_compression_level
Meaning: Compression level

Name: innodb_compression_pad_pct_max
Meaning: Maximum reserved free space in each compressed page.  Reserved free space is used when the page's data is reorganized and might be recompressed.

Name: innodb_concurrency_tickets
Meaning: Number of times a newly-entered thread can enter and leave InnoDB until it is again subject to the limitations of innodb_thread_concurrency and may possibly be queued.

Name: innodb_corrupt_table_action
Meaning: XtraDB only. Assert / warn / salvage

Name: innodb_data_file_path
Meaning: Individual InnoDB data files, paths and sizes. The value of innodb_data_home_dir is joined to each path specified by innodb_data_file_path to get the full directory path. If innodb_data_home_dir is an empty string, absolute paths can be specified here. A file size is specified with K for kilobytes, M for megabytes and G for gigabytes, and whether or not to autoextend the data file is also specified

Name: innodb_data_home_dir
Meaning: Directory path for all InnoDB data files in the shared tablespace

Name: innodb_deadlock_detect
Meaning: If set to off, deadlock detection is disabled and MariaDB will rely on innodb_lock_wait_timeout instead.

Name: innodb_deadlock_report
Meaning: Deadlock report detail: off / basic / full

Name: innodb_dedicated_server
Meaning: InnoDB automatically configures buffer pool and log file settings at startup

Name: innodb_default_row_format
Meaning: dynamic / compact / redundant

Name: innodb_directories
Meaning: List of directories separated by semicolons

Name: innodb_disable_sort_file_cache
Meaning: Disables the operating system file system cache for merge-sort temporary files. The effect is to open such files with the equivalent of O_DIRECT.

Name: innodb_doublewrite
Meaning: Dublewrite buffer feature enabled

Name: innodb_doublewrite_batch_size
Meaning: Number of doublewrite pages to write in a batch

Name: innodb_doublewrite_dir
Meaning: Directory for doublewrite files

Name: innodb_doublewrite_files
Meaning: Number of doublewrite files. By default, two doublewrite files are created for each buffer pool instance

Name: innodb_doublewrite_pages
Meaning: Maximum number of doublewrite pages per thread for a batch write. If no value is specified, set to the innodb_write_io_threads value

Name: innodb_fast_shutdown
Meaning: 0: purge and change-buffer merge. 1:skip those steps. 2:crash the program

Name: innodb_file_per_table
Meaning: When ON, tables are created in file-per-table tablespaces by default.

Name: innodb_fill_factor
Meaning: Space to fill in clustered index pages.  Never more than 94%.

Name: innodb_flush_log_at_timeout
Meaning: Write and flush the logs every N seconds

Name: innodb_flush_log_at_trx_commit
Meaning: 1: ACID.  0: Once per second.  2: logs written on commit, flushed once per second

Name: innodb_flush_method
Meaning: See https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/innodb-parameters.html#sysvar_innodb_flush_method

Name: innodb_flush_neighbors
Meaning: 0,1,2: Set to 0 on SSDs.

Name: innodb_flush_sync
Meaning: Causes the innodb_io_capacity setting to be ignored during bursts of I/O activity that occur at checkpoints

Name: innodb_flushing_avg_loops
Meaning: Increasing the value makes the rate of flush operations change smoothly and gradually as the workload changes. Decreasing the value makes adaptive flushing adjust quickly to workload changes, which can cause spikes in flushing activity if the workload increases and decreases suddenly

Name: innodb_force_load_corrupted
Meaning: Permits InnoDB to load tables at startup that are marked as corrupted. Use only during troubleshooting, to recover data that is otherwise inaccessible

Name: innodb_force_recovery
Meaning: 1-6. See https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/forcing-innodb-recovery.html

Name: innodb_fsync_threshold
Meaning: See https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/innodb-parameters.html#sysvar_innodb_fsync_threshold

Name: innodb_ft_cache_size
Meaning: Cache size for document in memory while creating an InnoDB FULLTEXT index

Name: innodb_ft_num_word_optimize
Meaning: Words to process during each OPTIMIZE run

Name: innodb_ft_sort_pll_degree
Meaning: Threads used for tokenizing and indexing full text

Name: innodb_ft_total_cache_size
Meaning: Total FULLTEXT cache size

Name: innodb_idle_flush_pct
Meaning: Limits page flushing when InnoDB is idle. A percentage of innodb_io_capacity.

Name: innodb_immediate_scrub_data_uncompressed
Meaning: Enable scrubbing of uncompressed data to overwrite deleted data

Name: innodb_io_capacity
Meaning: IOPS available to InnoDB background tasks, such as flushing pages from the buffer pool and merging data from the change buffer

Name: innodb_io_capacity_max
Meaning: Max IOPS available to InnoDB background tasks, such as flushing pages from the buffer pool and merging data from the change buffer

Name: innodb_lock_wait_timeout
Meaning: Max wait time for a row lock before rollback and 1205 error

Name: innodb_log_buffer_size
Meaning: Size of log file buffers.

Name: innodb_log_checksums
Meaning: Use checksums on redo log pages

Name: innodb_log_compressed_pages
Meaning: Re-compressed pages are written to the redo log. Re-compression may occur when changes are made to compressed data

Name: innodb_log_file_size
Meaning: Size of each file in a log group

Name: innodb_log_files_in_group
Meaning: Number of files in the log group

Name: innodb_log_spin_cpu_abs_lwm
Meaning: CPU core usage below which user threads no longer spin while waiting for flushed redo. (can be > 100 on multicore systems)

Name: innodb_log_spin_cpu_pct_hwm
Meaning: CPU core usage above which user threads no longer spin while waiting for flushed redo. (can be > 100 on multicore systems)

Name: innodb_log_wait_for_flush_spin_hwm
Meaning: Maximum average log flush time beyond which user threads no longer spin while waiting for flushed redo.

Name: innodb_log_write_ahead_size
Meaning: Write-ahead block size for the redo log. Even multiples of both filesystem and log fle block size.

Name: innodb_log_writer_threads
Meaning: Enables dedicated log writer threads for writing redo log records from the log buffer to the system buffers and flushing the system buffers to the redo log files. Dedicated log writer threads can improve performance on high-concurrency systems, but for low-concurrency systems, disabling dedicated log writer threads provides better performance.

Name: innodb_lru_scan_depth
Meaning: See https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/innodb-parameters.html#sysvar_innodb_lru_scan_depth

Name: innodb_max_dirty_pages_pct
Meaning: InnoDB tries to flush data from the buffer pool so that the percentage of dirty pages does not exceed this value.

Name: innodb_max_dirty_pages_pct_lwm
Meaning: Preflushing dirty page percentage. 0: disabled.  Must be lower than innodb_max_dirty_pages_pct

Name: innodb_max_undo_log_size
Meaning: If an undo tablespace exceeds the threshold, it can be marked for truncation when innodb_undo_log_truncate is enabled.

Name: innodb_scrub_log
Meaning: Enable redo log scrubbing to overwrite deleted data

Name: innodb_scrub_log_speed
Meaning: Redo log scrubbing speed

Name: innodb_undo_tablespaces
Meaning: Undo tablespaces to use

Name: innodb_use_fdatasync
Meaning: Use fdatasync() instead of sync() for performance

Name: innodb_use_native_aio
Meaning: Use the Linux asynchronous I/O subsystem.

Name: join_buffer_size
Meaning: The minimum size of the buffer that is used for plain index scans, range index scans, and joins that do not use indexes and thus perform full table scans.

Name: keep_files_on_create
Meaning: If a MyISAM table is created with no DATA DIRECTORY option, the .MYD file is created in the database directory. By default, if MyISAM finds an existing .MYD file in this case, it overwrites it. The same applies to .MYI files for tables created with no INDEX DIRECTORY option. To suppress this behavior, set the keep_files_on_create variable to ON (1), in which case MyISAM does not overwrite existing files and returns an error instead. The default value is OFF (0)

Name: key_buffer_size
Meaning: Size of MyISAM key cache.

Name: key_cache_age_threshold
Meaning: This value controls the demotion of buffers from the hot sublist of a key cache to the warm sublist. Lower values cause demotion to happen more quickly. The minimum value is 100.

Name: key_cache_block_size
Meaning: The size in bytes of blocks in the key cache. T

Name: key_cache_division_limit
Meaning: The division point between the hot and warm sublists of the key cache buffer list. The value is the percentage of the buffer list to use for the warm sublist.

Name: large_files_support
Meaning: Whether mysqld was compiled with options for large file support

Name: large_page_size
Meaning: If large page support is enabled, this shows the size of memory pages. Large memory pages are supported only on Linux; on other platforms, the value of this variable is always 0

Name: large_pages
Meaning: Whether large page support is enabled

Name: last_insert_id
Meaning: The value to be returned from LAST_INSERT_ID(). This is stored in the binary log when you use LAST_INSERT_ID() in a statement that updates a table.

Name: lc_time_names
Meaning: This variable specifies the locale that controls the language used to display day and month names and abbreviations

Name: license
Meaning: The type of license the server has

Name: local_infile
Meaning: This variable controls server-side LOCAL capability for LOAD DATA statements.

Name: lock_wait_timeout
Meaning: The timeout in seconds for attempts to acquire metadata locks.

Name: locked_in_memory
Meaning: Whether mysqld was locked in memory with --memlock.

Name: log_bin
Meaning: Enables binary logging

Name: log_error
Meaning: Error log output destination

Name: log_error_verbosity
Meaning: 1-Error messages; 2-Error and warning messages; 3-Error, warning, and informational messages

Name: log_output
Meaning: Combinations of TABLE, FILE, NONE

Name: log_queries_not_using_indexes
Meaning: If you enable this variable with the slow query log enabled, queries that are expected to retrieve all rows are logged.  This option does not necessarily mean that no index is used. For example, a query that uses a full index scan uses an index but would be logged because the index would not limit the number of rows.

Name: log_slow_admin_statements
Meaning: Include slow administrative statements in the slow query log.

Name: log_syslog
Meaning: Whether to write error log output to the system log.

Name: log_throttle_queries_not_using_indexes
Meaning: For queries expected to retrieve all rows, Limit their number per minute that can be written to the slow query log. 0: no limit.

Name: long_query_time
Meaning: If a query takes longer than this many seconds, the server increments the Slow_queries status variable. If the slow query log is enabled, the query is logged to the slow query log file. This value is measured in real time, not CPU time
